permanence_risk_evidence_and_reasoning:
Uncertainty in climate policy led to uncertainty in economic returns for landowners and in carbon storage in the short-, medium- and long-term;
2) Economic returns increased with the carbon price and as the expected regime switch became more imminent.
3) Carbon storage would increase with the carbon price until a saturation point after which higher carbon price ceased to enhance carbon storage;
4) The impacts of uncertain climate policy were more considerable on medium- and long-term carbon storage than on the short-term.

The approach presented in this paper was the first to address the impacts of uncertain timing of climate policy switches and among the very few capable of handling multiple sources of risk and uncertainty in carbon offset through sustainable management. It answered two critical questions: 1) for policy makers, how would a change in climate policy influence the decision making of forest landowners and alter forests and its associated ecosystem services? 2) for landowners, if a new climate policy was to be adopted, what would be the potential gain/loss and the best decision to make to adapt to this change? This proposed method would assist policy makers at different levels in projecting the potential extent to which climate policy shifts could impact the forest composition and carbon storage and in forecasting the revenue from managing carbon and timber stock. This framework would also help landowners, especially those with small lands or new ownership, understand the economic potential and risk imposed by climate policy uncertainty by illustrating in different policy scenarios, the short-, medium-, and long-term consequences of sustainable management practices and the highest financial returns from a combination of traditional timber sales and innovative carbon credits trades. In addition, we would provide them with optimal management guidelines in response to alternative policy regimes, in the form of straightforward decision tables, so they could cultivate their forests sustainably and profitably.
